The course aims to give a systematic overview of the institutional structure of the EU and the interaction of the key actors and their impact on EU policy making. Following the introduction of the main institutions and their role, the course discusses politics, policies and polity (i.e. the institutions) of the EU. It provides a platform for understanding the functioning of the EU and discusses its implications for policy-making at multiple levels of government. An relevant part of the discussion is devoted to the contextualization of the different modes of governance,Objectives/eesmärkid:  The aim of this course is to give an overview and understanding of the main principles of EU policy-making process and rules and practices governing the decision-making within and among the relevant institutions and bodies. Students will learn directly from the analysis of the treaties and of the primary sources. Particular attention is also devoted to the inter-institutional dimension and to the role of the Member states.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  Upon completion of the course, students will be able to: 

- Understand the mechanisms of policy-making in the EU and the institutional and policy-related processes; 

- critically assess the fuctioning and the roles of the main EU insitutions 

- contextualize and analyze the EU policy portfolio. 

- critically discuss the 'governance turn' in empirical and theoretical research on the EU; 

- Be able to critically examine the policy-related consequences of multi-level governance.
